Description:
  response: "**Description**\n\nThe dataset contains one million 311 service‑request records from New York City spanning the years 2010–2020. Each record is uniquely identified by a system‑generated integer (`Unique Key`) and captures the full lifecycle of a complaint: when it was created, closed, updated, and resolved, along with details such as agency, complaint type, location (address, ZIP code, borough, coordinates), status, and any resolution narrative. The data exhibit strong temporal concentration around 2015–2017, with the median creation date falling in late November 2015, while the overall spread covers a decade of service‑request activity. Spatially, most incidents cluster within the five boroughs, with latitude values ranging from roughly 40.11° to 40.91° and longitude values from –77.52° to –73.70°, reflecting New York City’s geographic extent.\n\n**Notable Characteristics**\n\n- **Temporal distribution**: Creation dates are heavily skewed toward the middle of the period, with a median near 2015‑11‑10 and 80 % of records created between 2013 and 2018. Closed dates lag behind by an average of ~1.4 years, indicating a long resolution cycle for many complaints.\n- **High cardinality vs. “Other” aggregation**: Many categorical fields (e.g., `Agency`, `Complaint Type`, `Descriptor`) contain thousands of distinct values, yet the top 10 are aggregated into an `\"Other (N)\"` bucket that covers >90 % of records, obscuring fine‑grained distributional detail.\n- **Missingness**: Approximately 3 % of records lack a closed date, while over 60 % have no due date. The `Resolution Description` is missing in only ~2 %, but the `Address Type` and `Borough` fields contain substantial nulls (~12 % each).\n- **Duplicate protection**: The `Unique Key` field guarantees one‑to‑one mapping between records and identifiers; no duplicate complaints exist in the sample.\n- **Location precision**: Latitude and longitude pairs are highly precise, but a small fraction of coordinates lie far outside Manhattan (e.g., latitude ~40.11° with longitude –77.52°, which is on Long Island), indicating potential data entry errors or out‑of‑city incidents.\n- **PII considerations**: While individual addresses and coordinate pairs can be used to approximate residential locations, the dataset does not contain personal identifiers; however, combining `Unique Key` with location may still facilitate re‑identification in highly specific contexts.\n- **Data quality flags**: The presence of “Other (N)” categories, high null rates for certain fields, and extreme coordinate values suggest that downstream analyses should account for potential sampling bias and perform robust missing‑data handling.\n\n*Attribution:* Generated by qsv v20.1.0 describegpt\nCommand line: target/debug/qsv describegpt --all --two-pass /tmp/NYC_311_SR_2010-2020-sample-1M.csv -o /tmp/nyc311-describegpt.toon --infer-content-type --format toon\nPrompt file: Default v7.1.0\nModel: openai/gpt-oss-20b\nLLM API URL: http://localhost:1234/v1\nLanguage: \nTimestamp: 2026-05-30T00:57:39.418032+00:00\n\nWARNING: Description generated by an LLM and may contain inaccuracies. Verify before using!\n"
